title: No longer works
reviewText: Update 11/24/19Wow. They just couldn't help themselves. Whatever they did during the last update broke the draw feature again. Now every time I open the app, it says Oops no results again. Can't believe this happened again. There needs to be more testing before these updates are released. I see a number of other reviewers experiencing the same thing. Unacceptable. Update 9/2/19Finally, the draw feature has been fixed with the last update. I have increased to three stars. Would be five stars, but now the most recent update has completely broken the property photo feature again rendering the app useless. All properties posted since the most recent update show absolutely no photos. Many of these properties have photos on Zillow, so it is clear that it is the Realtor app that is the issue. Again, this app should be better than the alternatives, but it is constantly plagued by update bugs that render it useless. Update: 7/2/19 just downloaded new update and issue is still not fixed. Been months. Poor job addressing user issues.——————————-I have been a loyal user of this app for a long time, but it is now riddled with error messages. Two updates ago, the draw area feature stopped working such that if you have a saved draw area, you get an error every time you open the app. This is a key feature for people looking to live in a particular area. I understood that there could be bugs with a new update. I patiently waited for another version to fix those bugs. It was released a few weeks ago. No fix. Still errors every time I open. Again, decided to give them another shot before writing a negative review. I just downloaded the most recent update and again, no fix for the errors. There are many people complaining about this issue in reviews, so the company is clearly aware. I can only assume that failing to fix these issues after two more updates is either a mark of ineptitude or frankly not caring about the customers they are alienating. I have now downloaded and use Zillow. Frankly, this app used to be far superior to Zillow in many ways, but it just doesn't work anymore, and fixing it doesn't seem to be a priority. Very unfortunate. For the records, I have uninstalled and reinstalled the app at least five times. That is not the problem as many users other than me are reporting.

title: Easy to use, efficient
reviewText: It does exactly what it should - finds, monitors, and alerts you to new listings that match your criteria. title: Intuitive App
reviewText: The Realtor.com app is provides accurate listings and is full of useful features and is extremely easy to use. Being able to either research the market for a specific area is instrumental when searching for a new home, and Realtor.com gives you a few great options for performing searches. You can open the app and search the market for houses in map mode then switch to list mode, so that you can quickly browse through the houses in the area selected. You can also add as many filters you wish, enabling you to see only those houses with the features you want included in your search. Once you have narrowed down your search, you can view the schools assigned to the zone the property is located in, although this part is not always accurate! I find myself manually entering the addresses in the city's districts website to find the appropriate schools. The app is limited by either the data entered by Realtors or Realtor.com's ability to match/ input the data from its sources, not sure! But overall a pretty accurate and intuitive app to use.

title: It Doesn’t Get Much Better Than This
reviewText: I love Realtor.com. I'm not ashamed to say so. I would get on my knee and give Realtor.com an engagement ring but I'm already married. From what I can tell, Realtor.com Has the most accurate and up-to-date information on properties. I have two suggestions for Realtor.com which I am hoping that, because I am making them public in this very posting, that they will take seriously.  The first is this: let's say I lived in California but I wanted to find a cheaper place to live then where I was currently living. Where would that be? After all, California is a pretty big place. Wouldn't it be nice if I could just go to Realtor.com and plug-in the word California? Realtor.com does not have that ability right now. I could plug-in every single county in California and get a response.  But that would be a lot of work. Wouldn't it be better if I could just type in the word California? And even better than that, wouldn't it be better if I could just plug in United States and get information on the entire country? So I hope that Realtor.com will take my thoughts very seriously and make this change. I don't think that will be very difficult at all. I have other apps for shopping which essentially is what Realtor.com does. I can for example look throughout the entire United States for a farm tractor that is four-wheel-drive built no earlier than 2005, It is made by Kubota, and has at least 40 hp. When I do this I can get returns from the entire country. Why not be able to get this when I'm looking for real estate? To me this seems very obvious. Here's my second request from Realtor.com: allow for videos. I realize that videos take more space than still pictures. Fine! Then I would be happy to pay more money if I were putting an ad in Realtor.com so that I could have a video of my property instead of just still pictures. If it's true that a picture is worth 1000 words, I think it's also true that a video is worth 1000 pictures. End of discussion!

But the fees are not always listed. For me, this is a "must have" number. Or a listing will list attractive HOA fees which are only attractive because there is another free added  to the mix called a "condo" fee.  Huh? What's the difference?  There really isn't any and it is quite misleading for the consumer. Another set of numbers I like to know is the sales history of a property.  This is oftentimes left out entirely. Again, this information is out there so why is it not reported? I realize that this app is only able to report the numbers that are provided so I believe that the real culprit here are the real estate listing companies, who provide the numbers.
